The Perimeter
[trigger none]

The dome wall curves away in both directions, close enough now to see the surface clearly. Not glass -- something layered, something that catches the light wrong. A door is set into the base. Flat metal, featureless, sized for something wider than a man.

An Iron patrol rounds the far edge of the dome, two figures moving in lockstep. They pass the door without stopping and continue along the curve until the dome swallows them from view.

You tighten your pack straps and settle your weight forward. Twenty yards of open ground between you and the door. You've outrun their patrols before.

"Don't."

The voice comes from behind a slab of collapsed masonry to your left. Before you can react, something sails past you -- an iron bolt with a scrap of cloth tied to its shaft. It lands on the bare ground maybe twenty feet ahead. The cloth flares red, bright enough to leave an afterimage, and crumbles to ash. The bolt hisses against the dirt, hot enough to scorch the earth around it.

A man steps out from behind the masonry. He's weathered the way decades outdoors will weather a person, skin creased and brown, hands steady. A leather case of surveying tools hangs at his hip, and a notebook is tucked under one arm.

"Torben. Imperial Survey, retired. Mostly." He nods at the scorched bolt. "Burn field. Invisible. Nasty way to die. Runs fifteen feet out from the wall, all the way around." He makes a little circle with his finger, as if to demonstrate.

He studies you for a moment, taking in the pack, your ring. "Trade Guild? Didn't realize you delivered this far out." He grins, then back to business. "I've been mapping this installation for three years. There's a route to the door, a gap in the field where it meets the threshold." He shrugs. "Won't do you much good. The door's sealed tighter than a merchant's purse. No offense."

He taps his notebook. "The Iron go in just fine. I suspect it's some sort of signal, like a code. I've heard there are imperial engineers out on the mid-plains working on restoring one of the old siege Iron. If anyone's figured out how those machines talk to each other, it'd be them."

choices:

* Go with him = Enter the city with Torben [requires has grid_cipher]
    You produce the grid cipher from your pack. Torben stares at it, then at you, then back at the device. "Where did you... No, don't tell me. I don't care." He's already moving, packing his gear with practiced ease.

    He leads you along a path only he can see, threading between the proximity field and the dome wall. At the door he steps aside and gestures. You hold the cipher out. Nothing happens for a moment. Then one by one bolt snap open inside the door. When the last unlocks the great door slowly grinds open.

    Torben is already through.

    "Stay close. Do exactly what I tell you. This will get dicey."
    +open "The Gauntlet"

* Depart = This place is beyond you
    You look at the scorched bolt on the ground, and the door, and the man who's spent three years trying to open it, and you decide that whatever is in there can stay in there.

    Torben nods. No judgment in it. "I understand. Safe travels." He settles back behind his slab of masonry and opens his notebook. He'll find someone else, or he'll wait. The notebook will get filled either way.
    +flee_dungeon
